It took medicine hundreds of years to stop using stuff as arsenic for anemia, x-rays for acne, etc., but current non-rational treatments (like iron for anemia or estrogen for acne) will follow suit. The future will resemble the past again, but better, more ergonomic conceptually.

Back in the day if you had tuberculosis you struggled brutally and died in misery and now you can just sit your ass on the couch taking antibiotics for a few months and be ok. Leprosy, deaths in childbirth, things that used to be pure horror for thousands of years just... solved.

"Video games are a waste of time" is a statement that obfuscates problems of faulty game design. Portal 2 is eight hours. Shit vidya sinks days. At different metas a League game could have been 45 minutes or sub-20 minutes average depending on balance. Good design prevents waste.

From what I understand this is Valve's exact philosophy with Counter-Strike 2, trying to degutter the gameplay as much as possible to minimize its "metabolic waste", shortening average round length and dead time of camping and inaction. A ~20 min game, sense of satisfaction, end.

Wearing a hiking tshirt to the gym is very cozy because you get the mental click association of adventure, exploration, etc. in a "safe", controlled environment, recreating the sensation of being in a tent or one of those forest cabins. Other cozy things: instant ramen w/ an egg.
Sir John Floyer

On the other side, wearing a gym tshirt hiking probably helps appreciate the more physiological elements of the experience like load on each step, lower back posture, etc. instead of focus on more romantic notions of nature. Other cozy things: a bottle of ginger ale with cheese.

Apologies on mentioning vidya again, but "A Story About my Uncle" is one of my favorite games, because it is pure movement. Nothing else except maneuvering through space without a floor even being present. Three hours to play through.

Very good example of a totally decluttered idea. Could have been overcomplicated with weapons, enemies, etc., but they kept the total focus on just moving from a point to another point using mechanics. Probably good to complete while listening to a radio show or podcasts or such.
It was developed by Swedish university students with the idea of making a non-violent FPS, but the "lack of violence" is the same as in figure skating or ballet, in spite of some medium limitations.

This is not my own thought and I am only extending it, but: "Right-wing twitter" is a carnival. A "clown fiesta". But this means nothing. Eventually all of life will be replaced with the carnival, just as it already happened once before at the end of the Medieval era with theirs.

People already often find "real life" and "twitter" overlap and in real situations one feels as if on twitter, but it is a carnivorous relation. One consumes the other. Soon those enjoying real life will wake up to find themselves enjoying the carnival as it spreads through them.

When people here ask what kind of woman or man they should get together with, the answer is: with someone from here. But eventually there will no longer be a here or a there. All will be here. The carnival-performers will fill their own audience. The world swallowed like a sword.
